“ It remains to say a word on the hiatus. In general, I may state that the sweeping corrections proposed by O. F. W. Miiller and the attempt made by Ritschl to obviate the hiatus by introducing a final d, after which there would still be left a number of refractory passages, have confirmed my former conviction as to the admissi- bility of hiatus in the caesura and when the line is divided among two or more speakers (Into-od. to Aul. p. Lx). But a new instance of hiatus should be added to those previously collected in my Introduction to the Aulularia: viz. hiatu-s before α’ cretio word ab the end of α line, such as we have it in V. 539 of the present play—

nam fulguritae sunt alternae arbores.

“This kind of hiatus was first pointed out by Spengel, and Brix adopted it in his note on Ilien. 473-

pranffl, potavi, scortum accubui: apstuli

and in a trochaic line, ib. 1160—

vaenibunt servi, supellex, aedes, fundi: omnia.

In the first place, it is evident that a correction would , spoil the style of the passage—though G. F. W. Miiller, who is up to anythjng‚ has the audacity to propose two conjectures5 m. that we should insert either inde or ei. In the second line it is just possible that Plautus wrote fandis or fundcis (even fundes), as Bucheler says in his valuable treatise on Latin Declension p. 18¹), but it is far from being proven.
